# Purpose

The v1.0 analysis (`nis_facial_nerve_supplement_query_v1.0_2026-04-27.qmd`)
identified 54 inpatient discharges with facial nerve repair codes assigned
to the Central Nervous System ICD-10-PCS section (00QM) rather than the
correct Peripheral Nervous System section (01QM). This pattern was
hypothesised to represent a systematic body-system assignment error.

This v1.1 analysis tests that hypothesis by examining the co-occurring
ICD-10-CM diagnosis codes on the 57 inpatient facial nerve repair cases
(3 correctly coded PNS + 54 miscoded CNS). If the diagnostic profiles of
the two groups are similar and clinically consistent with facial nerve
pathology, the miscoding interpretation is confirmed. If the diagnostic
profiles differ markedly, an alternative explanation must be sought.

**Diagnostic categories examined:**

- *Facial-nerve-consistent (positive evidence for miscoding hypothesis)*
  - Facial nerve disorders (G51.x)
  - Traumatic facial nerve injury (S04.5x)
  - Parotid neoplasms (C07, D11.0) \u2014 most common elective context
  - Vestibular schwannoma / CPA tumours (D33.3, C72.4x)
  - Temporal bone fracture (S02.1x)
  - Facial soft-tissue laceration (S01.4x, S01.8x)
  - Other cranial nerve disorders (G52.x)

- *Negative controls (would refute miscoding hypothesis)*
  - Spinal cord injury (S14.x, S24.x, S34.x)
  - Non-CPA brain tumours (C71.0\u2013C71.2)
  - Cerebrovascular accident (I60\u2013I63)

